the South Asian Medical Diaspora during the 1960s and 1970s -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe transnational migration of health care practitioners has become a critical issue in global health policy and ethics. Doctors beyond Borders provides an essential historical perspective on this international issue, showing how foreign-trained doctors have challenged – and transformed – health policy and medical practice in countries around the world.Drawing on a wide variety of sources, from immigration records and medical directories to oral histories, the contributors study topics ranging from the influence of South Asian doctors on geriatric medicine in the United Kingdom to the Swedish reaction to the arrival of Jewish physicians fleeing Nazi Germany and the impact of the Vietnam War on the migration of doctors to Canada. Combining social history, the history of health and medicine, and immigration history, Doctors beyond Borders is an impressive selection of essays on a topic that continues to have global relevance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEmigration and immigrationxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedicinexHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysiciansxHistoryy20th century. 0aTransnationalismxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Annika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBornat, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Barros, Juanita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsmail, Aneez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrenz, Margret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go